"Rypdal K., Berntsen T., Fuglestvedt J.S., Aunan K., Torvanger A., Stordal F., Pacyna J.M., Nygaard L.P.","Tropospheric ozone and aerosols in climate agreements: Scientific and political challenges",2005,"Environmental Science and Policy","8","1",,"29","43",,,10.1016/j.envsci.2004.09.003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-10944243792&partnerID=40&md5=0b72b19e9f8e545ffe92141c10d649ed","CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; NILU - Norwegian Inst. for Air Res., P.O. Box 100, N-2027 Kjeller, Norway","Rypdal, K., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Berntsen, T., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Fuglestvedt, J.S., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Aunan, K., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Torvanger, A., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Stordal, F., NILU - Norwegian Inst. for Air Res., P.O. Box 100, N-2027 Kjeller, Norway; Pacyna, J.M., NILU - Norwegian Inst. for Air Res., P.O. Box 100, N-2027 Kjeller, Norway; Nygaard, L.P., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129, Blindern N-0318 Oslo, Norway","In addition to the six greenhouse gases included in the Kyoto Protocol, the tropospheric ozone precursors CO, NMVOC and NOx and the aerosols/aerosol precursors black carbon, organic carbon and SO2 also play significant roles in climate change. The aim of this paper is to review some of the main scientific and political challenges associated with incorporating tropospheric ozone and aerosol precursors into climate agreements, and to discuss how these challenges have a bearing on the design of future climate agreements. We argue that the optimal policy design for a particular substance depends on a combination of scientific and political concerns. We look particularly at regional climate effects, negative forcing, metrics (measuring climate effects against other gases on a common scale), political attractiveness, and verification and compliance. We systematically review the existing knowledge on these issues, explore their impact on policy design, and conclude that, with current scientific knowledge, CO and NMVOC could conceivably be included in a global climate agreement, either in a basket with the long-lived greenhouse gases or in a separate basket, while NOx and aerosols might be regulated more appropriately through regional agreements with links to a global agreement. However, the complexity and fairness implications of including tropospheric ozone precursors and aerosols might negatively affect the political feasibility of a future agreement. © 2004 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Aerosols; Co-benefits; Cooling; Cost-effectiveness; Emission inventories; GWP; Ozone precursors; Radiative forcing; Regional agreements; UNFCCC convention","ozone; aerosol; atmosphere; climate change; concentration (parameters); environmental health; environmental impact; environmental monitoring; geographic distribution; greenhouse effect; priority journal; review",,"ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"Akimoto, H., Global air quality and pollution (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1716-1719; Aunan, K., Berntsen, T., Seip, H.M., Possible present and future agricultural crop loss due to surface ozone in China (2000) Ambio, 29, pp. 294-301; Aunan, K., Fang, J., Vennemo, H., Oye, K., Seip, H.M., Co-benefits of climate policy - Lessons learned from a study in Shanxi, China (2004) Energy Policy, 32 (4), pp. 567-581; Berglen, T., Isaksen, I., Sundet, J., A Global model for the coupled sulphur/oxidant chemistry of the troposphere: The sulphur cycle (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109 (D19), pp. D19310. , doi: 1029/2003JD003948; Berntsen, T., Isaksen, I.S.A., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Myhre, G., Larsen, T.A., Stordal, F., Freckleton, R.S., Shine, K.P., Effects of anthropogenic emissions on tropospheric ozone and its radiative forcing (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102 (D23), pp. 21239-21280; Berntsen, T., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Myhre, G., Stordal, F., Berglen, T.F., Abatement effectiveness of simulta